#!/usr/bin/env bash
# Run this locally (outside the remote container) to publish all 3 articles.
# Usage: bash scripts/seo-output/publish-all.sh

set -e

ENDPOINT="https://learnanything.pro/api/content/publish"
AUTH="Bearer 335644a93f2103b28f2a82c96b5ede6e3dadc39013877954b4a555fdd3c012c2"

publish() {
  local label="$1"
  local json="$2"
  echo "Publishing: $label"
  response=$(echo "$json" | curl -s -o /tmp/pub_response.json -w "%{http_code}" \
    -X POST "$ENDPOINT" \
    -H "Authorization: $AUTH" \
    -H "Content-Type: application/json" \
    --data-binary @-)
  echo "HTTP $response"
  cat /tmp/pub_response.json
  echo
}

# Article 1: PM Job Market 2026
publish "PM Job Market 2026" '{
  "title": "The PM Job Market in 2026: Why 7,300 Open Roles Still Feel Impossible to Land",
  "description": "More PM roles than ever—but they’re open 6–12 months. Here’s the signal collapse behind the paradox and what actually gets you hired now.",
  "vertical": "pm",
  "tags": ["pm-job-market", "product-manager-hiring", "career-growth", "ai-pm"],
  "primaryKeyword": "PM job market 2026",
  "sourceUrls": [
    "https://www.lennysnewsletter.com/p/state-of-the-product-job-market-in-ee9",
    "https://userpilot.com/blog/product-management-trends/",
    "https://www.mbassett.com/blog/navigating-product-management-in-2026/"
  ],
  "body": "The numbers look better than they have in years. Over 7,300 open PM roles globally — 75% above the 2023 low and up nearly 20% since January. Senior-level hiring is up 87% year-over-year. If you squint at the headline stats, the PM job market in 2026 looks like a recovery.\n\nIt doesn’t feel that way if you’re in it.\n\nRoles that filled in 6–8 weeks in 2022 are staying open for 6–12 months. Recruiters ghost after five rounds. Companies post and repost the same JD without actually moving candidates forward. This disconnect between “lots of jobs” and “can’t land one” is the defining frustration for PMs right now — and understanding why it happens is the first step to beating it.\n\n## The Signal Collapse Problem\n\nThe 2022 PM hiring market was noisy but fast. Volume compensated for poor signal. Hiring managers moved quickly because the opportunity cost of being slow was losing candidates to competitors.\n\nThat logic has inverted. In 2026, companies have more runway and more leverage. They can be selective because AI has reduced the urgency of backfilling PM seats — tasks that required a dedicated PM in 2022 are now handled by AI tools embedded in the engineer’s workflow. The result: companies are genuinely unsure what they want, so they leave the role open and wait for a signal that may never come on its own.\n\nFor candidates, this means the old playbook — apply broadly, nail the interview, wait — fails. You need to manufacture signal before you’re in the process.\n\n## What Companies Are Actually Hiring For\n\nThe PM role is splitting into three distinct tracks, and companies are hiring along those tracks deliberately:\n\n### Track 1: Technical / AI PM\nThese roles sit closest to engineering. They require genuine ML literacy: understanding model drift, training pipelines, data labeling quality, and inference costs at a conceptual level. AI PMs command an average of $245,000 in total comp versus $123,000 for traditional PMs — a $122,000 gap that has widened every quarter for two years. This is the starkest skill premium in any white-collar field right now.\n\n### Track 2: Growth / Monetization PM\nLifecycle, activation, retention, expansion revenue. These roles are closest to finance and marketing, and they’re being carved out explicitly as companies optimize unit economics rather than pure growth. If you’ve owned a conversion funnel or a retention initiative with data to back it, this is your track.\n\n### Track 3: Execution PM\nClassic product delivery and cross-functional coordination. These roles exist in volume and struggle to fill because candidates oversell their strategic scope and hiring managers undersell what they actually need. Competition is highest here because volume is highest here. If this is your target, your differentiation has to come from specificity: a specific domain, a specific type of product, a specific stack.\n\n## How the Interview Process Has Changed\n\nTraditional PM interviews tested product sense through open-ended questions: “How would you improve Spotify?” In 2026, the shift is toward demonstrated output.\n\n**Work samples are replacing brain teasers.** Expect to submit a real PRD, a competitor teardown, or a metrics-driven strategy memo before reaching a hiring manager. This step now filters out the majority of applicants.\n\n**Case challenges with data are standard at mid and senior levels.** You’ll get a dataset and 48–72 hours to produce a recommendation with supporting analysis. This tests whether you actually use data or just talk about it.\n\n**Portfolio reviews are table stakes at senior levels.** If you can’t point to 2–3 things you shipped, with data on what happened after launch, you’re not competitive for a Sr. PM role in this market. The degree requirement has largely disappeared. What hasn’t disappeared is the expectation that you can demonstrate thinking clearly and show receipts.\n\n## What Actually Works Right Now\n\n### Get specific about your track\n\nApplying to generic “PM” roles in 2026 is roughly as effective as applying to “tech job” roles was in 2010. Pick your lane — AI/technical, growth, or execution — and make every application artifact signal that lane. Your resume, your portfolio, your cover note, your LinkedIn all need to tell the same story.\n\n### Manufacture warm signal before applying\n\nThe roles staying open 6–12 months are cold-apply roles. They’re open because no signal has cut through. Get to the hiring manager through a shared Slack community, a conference, a LinkedIn post they engaged with, or a mutual introduction.\n\n### Build output in public\n\nWrite a strategy memo about a product you want to work on. Publish a teardown of a competitor’s pricing change. Post a thread breaking down why a feature launch succeeded or failed. In a market where work samples matter more than degrees, public output is a portfolio.\n\n### Target the 87% surge\n\nSenior-level hiring is growing nearly 5x faster than entry-level. If you’re a mid-level PM with 3–5 years of experience and concrete outcomes to show, you’re in the strongest position in this market. Target Sr. PM roles and frame your narrative around the scope those roles require.\n\n## One Metric to Track Your Job Search\n\nThe best PMs treat their job search like a product with a north star metric. In this market, that metric should be **qualified warm conversations per week**, not applications sent. Target 3 per week. If you’re consistently below that, the problem is your funnel.\n\n---\n\nThe PM market in 2026 is harder than the headline numbers suggest and more navigable than the pessimists claim. The work is getting specific, getting visible, and building output before you need it.\n\nPractice your product thinking daily at [PM Streak’s daily challenges](/daily-challenge), and check our curated [job board](/jobs) filtered by track. The right role is out there — the question is whether you’re positioned to find it when it matters."
}'

# Article 2: AI PM Salary Gap
publish "AI PM Salary Gap" '{
  "title": "The $122K AI PM Gap: How to Cross from Traditional PM to AI Product Manager",
  "description": "AI PMs earn $245K vs $123K for traditional PMs. Here’s the exact skill stack and 90-day transition plan to cross that divide in 2026.",
  "vertical": "pm",
  "tags": ["ai-product-manager", "career-growth", "pm-salary", "machine-learning", "skills"],
  "primaryKeyword": "AI product manager skills 2026",
  "sourceUrls": [
    "https://www.eicta.iitk.ac.in/knowledge-hub/product-management/ai-product-manager-skills",
    "https://amoeboids.com/blog/ai-skills-for-product-managers-2026/",
    "https://hbr.org/2026/02/to-drive-ai-adoption-build-your-teams-product-management-skills"
  ],
  "body": "In 2026, two product managers with equivalent seniority and experience can be $122,000 apart in total compensation. The difference isn’t their company, their negotiating skill, or their school. It’s one thing: whether they’re building AI-native products.\n\nAI PMs average $245,000 in total compensation. Traditional PMs average $123,000. That gap has widened every quarter for two years, and it’s not closing — it’s accelerating as companies increasingly build AI into the core of their products rather than as an add-on feature layer.\n\n## Why the Gap Exists (And Why It’s Not About Python)\n\nThe naive explanation is that AI PMs earn more because they can code. That’s wrong. AI PMs don’t write models, run training pipelines, or deploy ML infrastructure. They don’t need to.\n\nWhat they do differently is **scope the problem for AI-native solutions from first principles**. A traditional PM sees a problem and thinks: “What feature solves this?” An AI PM sees the same problem and thinks: “What data do we have? What model behavior would be acceptable? What does failure look like at scale? How do we detect model drift before users notice?”\n\nThat cognitive shift is worth $122K because it’s rare and impossible to fake in a technical conversation.\n\n## The Four Competency Gaps Most PMs Need to Close\n\n### 1. ML Literacy (Not ML Engineering)\n\nYou need to understand enough about how models work to have real conversations with data scientists and engineers — not to do their job, but to ask the right questions at the right moments.\n\nSpecifically, you need to know:\n\n- **Supervised vs unsupervised vs reinforcement learning**: what each is good for and where each breaks down, explained in terms of product use cases\n- **Model evaluation metrics**: precision, recall, F1, AUC — what they mean for your users, not just your data team\n- **Model drift**: why models that work well at launch degrade over time, and how to build monitoring into your product strategy from day one\n- **Inference costs**: why serving a large model at scale is expensive, and how that shapes your product roadmap decisions\n\nA practical test: can you read your data team’s model card or eval report and ask three non-obvious follow-up questions? If the answer is no, that’s your starting point.\n\n### 2. AI-Native PRD Writing\n\nA standard PRD specifies what a feature should do. An AI-native PRD does that and also specifies:\n\n- What the model’s target behavior is — with worked examples of ideal, acceptable, and disqualifying outputs\n- What failure modes exist and which are acceptable vs unacceptable\n- What human feedback loops exist — thumbs up/down, correction flows, implicit behavioral signals\n- How success will be measured when ground truth is ambiguous or expensive to label\n\nMost PM teams don’t have templates for AI-native PRDs. Writing one for a product in your current domain — even hypothetically — is one of the fastest ways to build credibility with AI engineering teams.\n\n### 3. Data Strategy as a Core PM Skill\n\nAI products are only as good as their training data, and the data flywheel is a product design problem as much as a data engineering problem. PMs who understand data strategy don’t just consume analytics — they architect feedback loops that make models better over time.\n\nThis means being able to answer:\n- What data does our product generate today that could train or fine-tune a model?\n- What is the cost and timeline of labeling that data?\n- What does the data flywheel look like — does our product get better as more users use it?\n\n### 4. AI Ethics and Regulatory Awareness\n\nThe EU AI Act is now in full effect, classifying AI systems by risk tier and imposing documentation, transparency, and human oversight requirements on high-risk systems. AI PMs need to classify product use cases by risk tier, write user-facing explanations of AI-generated content, and evaluate whether features create prohibited risk categories.\n\nThis isn’t compliance theater — it’s increasingly a launchability requirement.\n\n## The 90-Day Transition Plan\n\n### Weeks 1–4: Foundation\n- Complete fast.ai’s Practical Deep Learning for Coders (free, PM-appropriate framing)\n- Read your current product’s model documentation or eval reports\n- Write a shadow AI PRD for one feature your product already has\n\n### Weeks 5–8: Signal Building\n- Attend one data or ML review meeting per week with intent to ask one good question\n- Write and publish one analysis of an AI product decision a company made\n- Talk to one AI PM per week via LinkedIn DMs\n\n### Weeks 9–12: Portfolio Assembly\n- Write one complete AI-native PRD for a hypothetical product in a domain you know\n- Document the AI features at your current company with your analysis of their data strategy\n- Apply to 2–3 AI PM roles as a calibration exercise\n\nThe goal at 90 days isn’t a job offer. It’s being able to have a real conversation in an AI PM interview and know precisely what gaps remain.\n\n## Which Companies to Target First\n\nThe highest-compensation AI PM positions are at companies where AI IS the product:\n- **Foundation model labs** (highest compensation, highest technical bar)\n- **AI-native SaaS startups** (fastest learning, often highest equity upside)\n- **Big Tech dedicated AI product orgs** (structured onboarding, strong mentorship)\n\n## The Honest Tradeoff\n\nThe AI PM track pays significantly more and is significantly harder. It requires staying current in a field that changes faster than any previous technology cycle. The technical judgment you develop in year one may be partially obsolete by year three.\n\nThat’s the cost of the premium. If you’re energized by that rate of change, the career is exceptional. If you want stability, the traditional PM track is still strong — just a different choice with a different compensation ceiling.\n\n---\n\nStart building your AI PM skills today with [PM Streak’s daily challenges](/daily-challenge), which include AI product case studies and model evaluation exercises designed for PMs without engineering backgrounds. When you’re ready to prep for interviews, our [interview prep section](/interview-prep) covers AI PM-specific question types, including technical deep-dives into model evaluation, data strategy questions, and ethics scenarios."
}'

# Article 3: Senior PM Promotion
publish "Senior PM Promotion" '{
  "title": "How to Get Promoted to Senior PM: The Decision Bullet Framework That Actually Works",
  "description": "Most PMs fail promotion reviews because they confuse output with judgment. Here’s the specific framework that signals senior-level thinking to calibration panels.",
  "vertical": "pm",
  "tags": ["senior-pm-promotion", "career-growth", "product-manager", "pm-career", "promotion"],
  "primaryKeyword": "how to get promoted to senior PM",
  "sourceUrls": [
    "https://www.careerclimb.app/blog/how-to-get-promoted-to-senior-pm-at-meta",
    "https://dpereira.substack.com/p/how-pms-really-get-promoted",
    "https://www.leahtharin.com/p/leahs-2026-pm-career-guide-v1"
  ],
  "body": "Most product managers who get passed over for Senior PM promotion make the same mistake: they write their promotion case in output bullets.\n\n“Launched 3 features this quarter.”\n“Lifted activation by 12%.”\n“Led roadmap planning for Q3.”\n\nThese bullets describe execution. They do not describe judgment. And judgment — specifically, the ability to identify the right problem before being handed one — is what Senior PM calibration panels are actually evaluating.\n\n## What Actually Changes at the Senior PM Level\n\nThe difference is not about output volume, experience years, or team size. It’s about where the ambiguity lives.\n\n**At the PM level**: the problem is given to you. Your job is to figure out the solution. The ambiguity is in the “how.”\n\n**At the Senior PM level**: the problem itself is unclear. Your job is to find the problems nobody has identified yet, build internal consensus that they matter and deserve investment, and secure the resources to solve them. The ambiguity is in the “what.”\n\nThis explains why smart, high-performing PMs who execute brilliantly for years don’t get promoted — they’re operating at the “how” level when the calibration panel is asking “what” questions.\n\n## The Decision Bullet Framework\n\nThe core of a strong promotion case is replacing metric bullets with decision bullets.\n\n**Metric bullet**: “Increased D7 retention from 34% to 41% through onboarding improvements.”\n\nThis tells your manager you executed. It doesn’t tell them you made good decisions.\n\n**Decision bullet**: “Prioritized onboarding over the competing checkout flow initiative because retention data showed a 2x ROI payback period, overriding initial engineering preference. D7 retention moved from 34% to 41% as a result.”\n\nThe difference: a decision bullet shows that you saw a fork in the road, made a defensible call when there was pressure to make a different one, and achieved the result. That’s what senior-level judgment looks like in writing.\n\n### How to Retro-Fit Your Last 12 Months\n\nGo through every significant outcome you owned in the past year and ask: “What was the non-obvious decision I made that other reasonable people might have made differently — and why was mine right?”\n\nIf you can’t identify a decision like this for an outcome, that’s diagnostic. Either you were executing a plan handed to you (not senior PM work), or you were making decisions but not claiming ownership of them in your narrative (fixable immediately).\n\n### The Three-Part Decision Bullet Formula\n\n1. **The fork**: what were the alternatives?\n2. **The call and the reasoning**: which did you choose and why, especially if it went against something?\n3. **The outcome**: what happened as a result?\n\n## Why Calibration Is Where Promotions Actually Die\n\nIn calibration — the cross-functional meeting where promotion decisions are made — your manager presents your case, and then someone says “I don’t have enough visibility into their work to have a view” — and that absence of signal reads as insufficient evidence for promotion.\n\nThe promotion threshold is effectively two things at once: operating at the next level AND being known at the next level. A strong record without cross-org visibility fails. Visibility without the record fails. You need both.\n\n## The Three Visibility Levers That Actually Work\n\n### 1. Strategy Memos\n\nWrite a 2-page strategy memo about something you believe that the company hasn’t fully articulated yet. Not a roadmap document — a point of view. Share it with your manager first. Ask if it’s appropriate to share with adjacent team leads or leadership. A strategy memo that gets forwarded becomes currency. A single well-circulated memo can do more for your promotion case than a quarter of solid execution.\n\n### 2. All-Hands Presence\n\nVolunteer to present at product all-hands, even for a 5-minute update on what your team learned from a recent launch. One well-received all-hands slot is worth more for calibration than three months of quiet execution.\n\n### 3. Cross-Team Strategy Reviews\n\nWhen adjacent teams are doing roadmap planning or strategy reviews, ask if you can sit in or contribute input. Better: proactively offer to share learnings from your team that might affect their planning decisions. PMs who operate across team boundaries without being asked are demonstrating senior scope.\n\n## The Calibration Readiness Question\n\nSix weeks before the next review cycle, ask your manager directly: “If my name came up in calibration today, who in the room would speak up for me, and what would they say?”\n\nIf your manager can’t name at least two people outside your immediate team who would speak positively about your work, you have your gap. The work isn’t to improve your execution. The work is to increase your visible footprint through the three levers above.\n\n## The Mistake of Waiting to Be Told You’re Ready\n\nSix to eight weeks before the cycle, ask: “What would make the case for Senior PM undeniable at the next calibration? Give me the two or three specific things.” Then execute exactly those things. Not more. Not adjacent improvements. Exactly those things.\n\nA calibration panel looking for a reason to promote you will find one if you’ve given them a clear, specific narrative. Give them the narrative. Then make the case undeniable.\n\n---\n\nPromotion to Senior PM isn’t a reward for effort or tenure. It’s recognition that you’re already operating at that level with visibility to prove it.\n\nBuild your product thinking every day on [PM Streak’s daily challenges](/daily-challenge), and when you’re ready to prepare your promotion story and interview for Senior PM roles, visit our [interview prep section](/interview-prep) for Senior PM walkthroughs tailored to FAANG-style and growth-stage calibration panels."
}'

